From the recent exam results of this year, we can conclude that languages are at the top of the ranking list, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages scored a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools joined SCIS, shows that 72 percent of students achieved a high score ('A') in Mandarin, while 72 percent of students received German, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as much as STEM subjects (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
An investigation by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that 17% of the obstacles to filling in job vacancies were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Language skills thus become increasingly important to prepare young people for their future career.
More and more jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that a person chooses, when he has learned a second language, in the future he has a real advantage with such a skill for life.
Directly communicating with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person a lead to competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% was unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation. French was the only language that was above 10%, with a total of 15%.
This is why investment in language education is now important to the children of today.
Several languages, in particular those of emerging economies, will offer children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach themselves.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the United Kingdom when they look ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specialised in this field.
Scottish independent schools work to provide a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
At present it cannot be denied that languages in a global business environment remain vitally important for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered as 'international communication skills.'
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
