Hiv/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14% new cases
China reports that the number of Chinese with HIV and AIDS increased by 14%.
Health authorities say that more than 820,000 people have been affected in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, 40,000 new cases were reported.
In the vast majority of new cases, the diseases were passed on via sex, which was not the case before.
Hiv has spread rapidly in some parts of China in the past through transfusions of contaminated blood.
But the number of people who are on the rise in this way is now almost zero, said Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, compared to the same period last year, the number of people with HIV and AIDS in China increased by 100,000.
The transmission of HIV via sex is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality is no longer punishable in China since 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is said to be widespread.
According to studies, the conservative values of the country are estimated to marry 70 to 90% of men who have sex with men in the end.
The disease is often transmitted by insufficient protection in sexual relations in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medication in the context of efforts to tackle the problem.
