National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
New research carried out on a estate in the Scottish highlands, tries to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study carried out by scientists of the National Trust for Scotland follows the common and small dwarf bat, the brown large bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment shall be placed on key locations around the estate to track the activities of the bats throughout the season.
NTS and volunteer staff will also carry out mobile investigations using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the wings of the bat and what kind does.
A map of the habitat and a report is then produced to make a detailed picture on landscape scale of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation consultant, hopes that the results show the habitat's main areas for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of pasture fields and how we can best maintain forests for bats and similar species.
In Scotland and in the rest of the UK, bat populations have decreased significantly in the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities affecting sleeping places and the loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lightnings can also pose a risk, such as flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
In reality, bats are not blind.
But their nocturnal hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
At the NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares ashore in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts who conduct regular investigations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species of bats of Scotland live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says that the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Threat we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But there is so much not yet known about bats and therefore the work we do here and at other locations will help us to understand better what they need to thrive."
He stressed the importance of control of bats before maintenance activities were carried out, as the possibly unconscious destruction of a sleeping place could lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, which might eliminate a complete local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, to trouble them or to disturb them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and of many of our species we just don't know how their populations are."
